{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_douglasfir_ver01/data/sn86075189/00414211021/1948101501/0421.xml":{"full_text":"TTTZ~T~~JZ~.\nT\nJ\n\nV?\nLsmn\nHiK r r r flirrn UhH\nWIDe INDEPENDENT NEWSPAPER\n''MONTANA'S\nPublished weekly by The People's Voice Publishing Co. at 1205 Lockey Street\nHelena, Montana\nPhone 26-J\nP. O. Box 838\nH. S. BRUCE, Managing Editor\nHARRY L. BILLINGS, Editor\nCO-OP PUBLISHING\nCO., HELENA, MONT.\nEntered as Second Class Matter December 7, 1939 at the Post Office at\nHelena, Montana, under the Act of March 3, 1879.\nUj\nSubscription Price: $2.00 Year; Trial Subscription: Five Months $1.00\nNo Commercial Advertising except from Co-operative Business\ninstitutions accepted. Rates on application.\nM. P. Discourages Sales\nC\nIt is generally assumed that when an increase in volume\nof sales is attained by any well conducted commercial or in\ndustrial enterprise, a reduction in the unit cost to the purchaser\nor consumer ^s made possible. Ordinarily also, the common\npractice of commercial or industrial enterprises is to make con\nstant appeal for increased consumption or sale of the articles\nor services sold. And everyone realizes that the most potent\nappeal to the purchaser, lies in reduced prices for larger\nquantities.\nThe recent residential rate increase in the price of electric\npower, approved by the Railroad and Public Service Commis\nsion for the Montana Power company, goes entirely contrary\nto the ordinary policies of commercial and industrial indicated\nabove. The Montana resident who might plan on increasing\nhis purchase of electric power by installation of additional\nfacilities for use finds that he will be penalized by an increased\ncost of the additional electric energy required for their opera\ntion. It is clearly indicated that the Montana Power company\nwants to discourage more consumption of electric energy for\ndomestic uses. This raises the interesting question of why the\ncompany should deliberately move to discourage greater con\nsumption of the product and services it sells.\nThere would appear to be only one answer to that riddle.\nThe power company must be afraid that any pronounced in\ncrease in sale of power to residential users, would disclose the\nshortage of required power with which it is faced. While the\ncompany has again and again asserted that it was producing\nand had available more power than was needed to meet the\nrequirements of the state, nevertheless it has been unable to\nexplain why, for instance, some REA lines already constructed\nnot bring service to farms the lines were supposed to\nprovide with electric energy.\nThere is also the possibility that the Montana Power com\npany anticipating success in the efforts of the private power\nutilities to secure legislation from a reactionary congress for\nexclusive sale to them of power produced by government con\nstructed dams, is prepared in advance for further gouging of\nthe residential consumers. The average farm on an REA line\ncould use much power to ease the work burden, by installation\nof electrically operated facilities; milking machines, cream\nseparators, washing machines, pumps, refrigerators, deep\nfreeze units and other facilities which would make farm life\neasier and more pleasant. But such installations would un\ndoubtedly bring power consumption above the point where the\nincreased rates go into effect. And the easy money profits\nfor the company would, of course, increase rapidly.\nThe bitter fight which is now being waged by the private\npower companies against the construction of transmission lines\nplanned by the government which would carry publicly pro\nduced power direct to consumers, is a fight for preservation of\nexploiting monopoly. It is a fight against the personal in\nterests of every individual citizen of the country. To bring this\nclearly before you, it is only necessary to cite one example right\nhere in Montana. Power produced at the Fort Peck govern\nment dam is sold to the Montana Power company at Great\nFalls for 2^4 mills but resold to the consumers for nine mills\nor nearly four times what it costs the company. The rate of\nprofit is actually 360%.\nDuring the special session of congress, Senator Murray\nfought to secure an additional appropriation for the construc\ntion of a transmission line from Havre to Shelby for the trans\nmission of Fort Peck produced power to the farmers in that\nsection who have already formed a co-operative, and have gone\nto great expense to lay out their project, but he was defeated.\nThe people in that section particularly, and the people through\nout Montana generally, should take notice of the attitude their\nother senator \"Buddy\" Ecton. He not only voted against the\nincrease appropriation proposed by Senator Murray but spoke\nagainst it on the floor of the senate.\nI hope that the people of Montana do not have too short\nmemories to remember this and other actions of Ecton, should\nhe again be a candidate for the senate.\nAnd I hope that the people of the state show their appre\nciation of the work in their behalf by Senator Murray this\nyear by giving him the largest vote ever given to a candidate.\nHelp the Poor ACM\nThe Tom Davis for Senator Club in Butte has sent out a\nplea to the public, in which the people are asked to contribute\nto the Davis campaign. The letter states that \"A dollar or\nmore invested in freedom is not much\". And of course all of\nthose contributing a dollar or more are asked to\npersonal work for Tom\". The freedom which Tom is to \"help\npreserve,\" is \"freedm from regimentation, socialism and other\nBureaucratic forms of dictatorship\" according to the letter.\nThe \"political dictatorship\" which the ACM company\nU\ndo some\ncon\na\nFOR THIS THEY DIED?\na\nEvents of recent weeks can in no wise be chalked\nup as fruitful steps'along the hard road to world\nrehabilitation and genuine democracy for all men.\nRather, the activities of our state and defense depart\nments indicate that we've not only\nbroken solemn pledge after pledge\nmade during World War II, but,\nshould World War III come, not a\nlittle of the guilt will rest squarely\non the shoulders of Uncle Sam.\nd\u00e9 'V* 1\nUnder Roosevelt we pledged our\nselves to militantly co-operate in\nstamping out every vestige of fas\ncism, no matter where it reared its\nugly head in the world.\nUnder Roosevelt it was fashion\nable to whole-heartedly condemn the black-hearted,\nmurderous regime of Francisco Franco in Spain.\nUnder Roosevelt, nazi saboteurs caught off Long\nIsland and the Florida coast were promptly brought to\ntrial, executed, or given long-term prison sentences.\nUnder Roosevelt a sincere feeling of goodwill was\nextended to Jews everywhere in their aspirations to\nestablish a national homeland in Palestine.\nM.\nUnder Roosevelt few stones were left unturned in\nbuilding good will and friendship for America the\nworld over. Our nation assumed not only a com\nmanding role militarily, but, more important still, re\nspect was fast developing for the moral leadership we\nwere exerting in the planning of a more abundant,\nmore prosperous, peaceful world for all peoples.\nTHE PICTURE CHANGES\nBut enunciation of these ideals came during the\nRoosevelt era. As was FDR buried at Hyde Park,\none by one his ideals too have been buried as the\nHerbert Hoovers, the Foster Dulles' and the George\nMarshalls gradually moved in to dominate his hapless\nsuccessor.\nToday it's the vogue that we no longer condemn\nand extirpate the brutal leadership of the fascists.\nToday our Lucius Clays pardon instead of hanging\nsuch monsters as Use Koch.\nNo longer shall Franco be consigned to the black\nest hell he so richly deserves,\nof state contends\nunjustified This murderer and his fascist dic\ntatorship shall now be permitted to receive American\narms\u2014if George Marshall has his way.\nNazi saboteurs, lucky enough to escape the noose\nin 1942, have now been quietly pardoned by President\nTruman at the behest of Secretary of the Army\nKenneth Royall.\nToday our secretary\nthe ban on Franco is\nA similar breaking of faith is our double-crossing\nof the people of Israel. Roosevelt sought to have\nestablished an independent national home for the\nJews. The Democratic party platform of 1944\nunequivocal in support of FDR, stating \"We favor\nthe opening of Palestine to unrestricted Jewish im\nmigration and colonization, and such a policy as to\nresult in the establishment there of a free and demo\ncratic Jewish commonwealth.\"\nTruman pays lip service and George Marshall, by ap\nproving the Bernadotte proposals, paves the way for\nthe total dismemberment of the Jewish state, in favor\nof the British-dominated Arabian neighbors of Israel.\nwas\nTo this President\nFinally, so far as FDR's \"good neighbor\" policy\nis concerned, it no longer exists,\nbia, General Marshall and other Americans\nbooed.\nIn Bogota, Colum\nwere\nSouth American countries now look to Mexico\nand Argentina for leadership,\nour prestige is slipping badly because of the\nerous political and economic strings attached to the\nso-called European Recovery Plan,\nforce an outward appearance of respect, but, it alone\nwill never buy the friendship of exploitation-weary\nEuropeans. Already France is casting a worried eye\nat our insistence that western Germany's war industry\nbe rebuilt. Frenchmen of all political faiths cannot\nin western Europe\nnum\nOur money can\nstantly tries, and often successfully, to\ncise in Montana, is undoubtedly not included\nin the agenda of the things that Tom would\nfight against. It is well understood by the\nvoters of the state that he is the outstanding\nchoice of the ACM company and its twin, the\nMontana Power company. Since the choice\nlies between Senator Murray and Tom Davis,\nthere can be no question as to which one of\nthese two the \"Montana Twins\" favors. Sen\nator Murray has the active enmity of the\n\"twins\" because of his independence and his\nprotection of the interests of the public\nagainst the machinations of these exploiting\ncorporations.\nIt is interesting to note the close relation\nship of Tom Davis with the ACM company\nas indicated by the Butte club organization.\nThe secretary of the club is Marguerite I.\nShea, said to be the wife of a geologist for\nthe company and the chairman of the finance\ncommittee is Wm. A. O'Kelly who has been\nchief mining engineer for the ACM for 19\nyears.\nThe cynic who received one of these letters\nand sent it to The Voice called the lady\nwhose name appears as president of the club,\nthe \"wife of the undertaker that buries ACM\nRepublicans in Silver Bow County after every\nelection\". He didn't say so, but it might be\nsuspected that he hopes that this undertaker\nwill be very busy after November 2 this year.\nH. S. BRUCE.\nexer\neasily forget three Germanic invasions over the last\n75 years. Further, they've informed our country that\ncivil war will rage if we attempt to force them to bear\narms in the interests of American cartelism. Similar\nsentiments come from Italy. Those people ai'e sick\nunto the death of war, pestilence, famine\u2014desire only\npeace and a chance to rebuild their countries.\nBut\u2014we persist in our madness. Russia must be\n\"contained\" even if we have to \"atomize\" the entire\nglobe to effect such containment, and solidly entrench\nAmerican monopolists in every one of the wprld'i\noutposts.\nTO BLEED, TO DIE\nSurely this isn't what 300,000 young Americans\nso recently gave their lives for; or for what several\nhundred thousand others will spend the remainder of\ntheir days as cripples, or inmates of mental institu\ntions. Surely this isn't what the parents of America\nare raising new generations of sons for\u2014to bleed and\ndie on new battlefields because 'of broken promises\nand the inexhaustible greed of American capitalists.\nBUT\u2014that's just what's going to happen unless you\nand you and you raise your voices in thunderous pro\ntest immediately.\nDon't think \"It can't happen again\"\u2014it can\u2014and\nRetiring Senator Capper (R, Kansas) made\nmay.\nthis very plain Sunday when he told Associated Press:\n\"The United States is moving in several directions\nto prepare for the eventually\u2014war.\" And, that offi\ncial bi-partisan policy is to make no such acknowl\nedgement (of that eventually), at least not before\nthe elections are over.\"\u2014HLB\n\u2022J\u00ab \u00bbJ\u00ab \u25baJ*\nWALL STREET'S ADVICE TO\nTOM DEWEY\nOne of the country's leading financial journals. BAR\nRON'S National Business and Financial Weekly, has\ncome up with some advice for Tom Dewey, who it as\nsumes will be the next President of the U.S. The sug\ngestion: manipulate government policies to bring about\nan early depression,\nlined,\nsaid\nUnder a frontpage editorial head\nPolitical Value of Possible Slump.\" the paper\n\"The present boom in business is ten years old.\nthe nature of things, its end seems wholly likely to\nrive sometime before the political campaign of 1952.\nIf at that time Dewey should want to run for re-election,\nwith the hope of a successful second term, he would\nlook with dismay upou the arrival of a depression in\nIn\nar\n1951 or 1952.\nThe only way he could try to avoid such\na contingency would be to shape federal policies toward\ndeflation as early as possible in 1949. A recession tak\ning place so soon could easily be blamed on the Truman\nadministration, and efforts toward recovery could be\nmade once the medicine were taken,\ncould be regarded as the man who had rescued the na\ntion from a dangerous setback in prosperity.\"\nWith luck, Dewey\nDEPRESSIONS DESIRABLE\"\nThe editorial (7-26) goes on to \"blame\" the Demo\ncrats for preventing a recession, and reflects the view\nthat our economy is unhealthy without a pool of mil\nlions unemployed. This advice parallels other big busi\nness statements that what the country needs is a good,\ndepression.\nThe trade journal, \"Automotive and Avia\ntion Industries.\" carried an article by Ralph Blodgett\nsome time ago declaring:\npressions are never abolished, for they have many de\nsireable features,\nappropriate.\nIt is to be hoped that de\nThat very name 'depression' is in\nIt horribly maligns those great periods\nso full of splendid opportunities and human benefits,*\nLet us keep those periods and abolish only the\n\u2014IN FACT, 280 LaFayette St., New York 12, N.Y.\nSuch as farm foreclosures, soup lines and small\nbusiness failures, we presume.\nname.\n\nu\nCYNICAL DEMONSTRATION\n99\nThe Chicago Daily News observed August 25:\nThe excessive zeal of Democratic politicians in\nIllinois and elsewhere to deny the electorate an op\nportunity to vote for Henry Wallace and his disciples\nis a cynical demonstration of how far machine bosses\nwill go to protect their vested interests.\nCompare the torrent of technical objections\nthe Progressive Party petitions with the easy accept\nance of the candidacy of Elmer H. Droste, the Repub\nican nominee for state treasurer, in whose petitions\nthe most casual observer could\nto\nr see wholesale forgery.\nWe condemn the effort to deny them (Progres\nsives) a place on the ballot by a totally dishonest\ntense of reverence for\nlaws.\"\npre\nevery comma of the election\n\u2022P *\u00ee\u00ab\nFarm Costs Up 14%, Income Up Only 4%\nThe U.S. Department of Agriculture revealed fig\niii es this week indicating that cash receipts from farm\nmarketings would amount to about $18 billions. This\nsum is 4% above the same period for 1947. More signif\nmo/ f f Ct thEt farmers during this period paid\n4 /e MORE tor goods used in production than they\npaid during the same period last year. Thus real farm\nincome has shown a substantial decline.\u2014NFU in Wash\nington.\n\u2022F\nWords are stronger than atom bombs\nand the heart\nof man is the most powerful thing in the universe \"_\nHENRY A. WALLACE.\n*r\nLife is not so short but what there i\nalways time enough for courtesy\"\u2014Anon.\n\nIS","height":"20109","width":"13962"}}
